          "title": "Eighty valiant priests — institutional courage under royal pressure",
          "body": "The confrontation in vv.17-18 is frequently underread. Eighty priests enter the temple after Azariah. The Chronicler calls them *chayil* — valiant, the same word used for Uzziah's elite soldiers. They are not bureaucrats defending procedure; they are described in the language of military courage. They 'took their stand' (*amad*) against the king and delivered a two-part oracle: (1) this is not your right; (2) you have been unfaithful. The confrontation has the force of a prophetic declaration within the sanctuary. Douglas Moo's principle about institutional authority is relevant here: the structures God ordains for the protection of His people require human agents willing to enforce them at personal risk. These priests risk royal wrath to defend a boundary they did not create. Their courage is vindicated immediately — not by their own argument but by God's direct action while they are still speaking. Uzziah's rage in v.19 shows that the confrontation was necessary precisely because he was not going to stop voluntarily."
